Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 10:13:59 -0500
From: Evanko, Robert <robert.evanko@csfb.com>

As a layman who's been subscribed to this list for 2 years, it's starting
to look like we can't see the forest for the trees on the topic of
xenotransplantation, the first issue should be to differentiate between
normal, screened & purified animal organs such as baboon hearts from
animals raised in a sterile environment versus genetically altered organs
grown by a host animal (perhaps a genetically human liver plugged into a
pigs body to grown until harvested). The recent creation of artificial raw
stem cells appears to be leading to the latter solution in the near future.
If we look at the first category it appears to me that the recipient will
have to beware of pathogens that have an effect on the donated organ but
not other pathogens from the host animal because the human immune system
should provide some protection & no other organs will have the correct
receptors for these pathogens, only the transplant.
Regarding the latter classification, I guess debate will begin in the
scientific community whether these organs are human or animal, will these
organs be immune to the host's pathogens, will pathogens mutate to adapt to
the human genome any faster than through the mixing bowl of nature? On the
flip side, it may be possible to incorporate a genetically altered organ
from a host animal that will be resistant or even immune to human pathogens.
There is always a risk for every reward.
--
Robert Evanko
CS First Boston
11 Madison Avenue
New York, NY 10010
e-mail: robert.evanko@csfb.com
