[2
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 11:15:45 -0500
From: Bill Graney <wmgraney@bellatlantic.net>

The experience with porcine valves may have limited applicability to live
organ xenotransplantation. The valve material is thoroughly denatured
during processing and there is simply no issue of infectious agents
surviving. (I suppose that all bets are off for the BSE agent, but for
other organisms there appears to be no risk.)
I believe that most of the concern with xenotransplantation has centered on
animal viruses, latent or lively, which would proliferate in the
immunosuppressed host. Another AIDS is the nightmare scenario.
The biological, regulatory, and social issues have been well examined and
can be followed in 2 threads:
1) An extensive discussion in Nature Medicine. You can pick it up with an
editorial and a news article in the February 98 issue.
2) The development of FDA's policy and moratorium. The transcripts of a
meeting on "Developing USPHS Policy in Xenotransplantation" are available
on the FDA web site. Just search on Xenotransplantation.
>From the point of view of a clinical research manager, one of the most
interesting implications is the need to follow the recipients family and
care givers for the development of infection/disease for long periods (years).
I believe the issues are far from settled.
--
Bill Graney, M.D.
Collegeville, PA
e-mail: wmgraney@bellatlantic.net
