[3
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 10:19:14 -0500
From: Stephen Johnson <stephenjohnson@pol.net>

Regarding the comments on the safety of porcine cardiac valves in humans
and the attempts to extrapolate to organ xenotransplantation, the most
obvious difference is that the host receiving an organ transplant is
severely immunocompromised (to prevent rejection). There is also the issue
of more heterogenous tissues being transplanted with organs (with the
possibility of carrying organisms with particular tissue tropisms) in
contrast to the porcine valve. These issues (and possibly others) make
extrapolation of infectious risks from porcine valve transplantation to
organ xenotransplantation a potentially dangerous sport, if it was to be
put into practice without experimental evaluation (which obviously no one
is advocating).
--
Stephen Johnson, MD DTM&H
HealthOne
Denver, Colorado
e-mail: stephenjohnson@pol.net
[Apropos the last point, this summer I managed to catch up with a classmate
of mine, Richard Medd, after a gap of some 25+ years. In the American and
British senses of the word I 'visited' (with) him for three days and we got
caught up. I discovered that he had been part of the Cambridge
heart-transplant team and responsible for the animal transplant model
constructions & surgery and, among other organ transplants with pigs and
such, routinely carried out mouse heart transplants, which boggles the
average mind. Presumably those developing porcine xentransplants will be
involved in similar inter-species organ transplants and monitoring the
results, hopefully over prolonged periods? If so, have they published their
results? - Mod.MHJ ...........................................mhj/es
